  9  # Specific classes of maps between topological spaces
 10  
 11  This file introduces the following properties of a map `f : X → Y` between topological spaces:
 12  
 13  * `is_open_map f` means the image of an open set under `f` is open.
 14  * `is_closed_map f` means the image of a closed set under `f` is closed.
 15  
 16  (Open and closed maps need not be continuous.)
 17  
 18  * `inducing f` means the topology on `X` is the one induced via `f` from the topology on `Y`.
 19    These behave like embeddings except they need not be injective. Instead, points of `X` which
 20    are identified by `f` are also indistinguishable in the topology on `X`.
 21  * `embedding f` means `f` is inducing and also injective. Equivalently, `f` identifies `X` with
 22    a subspace of `Y`.
 23  * `open_embedding f` means `f` is an embedding with open image, so it identifies `X` with an
 24    open subspace of `Y`. Equivalently, `f` is an embedding and an open map.
 25  * `closed_embedding f` similarly means `f` is an embedding with closed image, so it identifies
 26    `X` with a closed subspace of `Y`. Equivalently, `f` is an embedding and a closed map.
 27  
 28  * `quotient_map f` is the dual condition to `embedding f`: `f` is surjective and the topology
 29    on `Y` is the one coinduced via `f` from the topology on `X`. Equivalently, `f` identifies
 30    `Y` with a quotient of `X`. Quotient maps are also sometimes known as identification maps.
 31

 33

103    and for all `s : set α`, `s` is open iff it is the preimage of an open set. -/
